</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Fatty liver disease comprises a spectrum of conditions (simple hepatic steatosis, steatohepatitis with inflammatory changes, and end-stage liver disease with fibrosis and cirrhosis). Hepatic steatosis is often associated with diabetes and obesity and may be secondary to alcohol and drug use, toxins, viral infections, and metabolic diseases. Detection and quantification of liver fat have many clinical applications, and early recognition is crucial to institute appropriate management and prevent progression. Histopathologic analysis is the reference standard to detect and quantify fat in the liver, but results are vulnerable to sampling error. Moreover, it can cause morbidity and complications and cannot be repeated often enough to monitor treatment response. Imaging can be repeated regularly and allows assessment of the entire liver, thus avoiding sampling error. Selection of appropriate imaging methods demands understanding of their advantages and limitations and the suitable clinical setting. Ultrasonography is effective for detecting moderate or severe fatty infiltration but is limited by lack of interobserver reliability and intraobserver reproducibility. Computed tomography allows quantitative and qualitative evaluation and is generally highly accurate and reliable; however, the results may be confounded by hepatic parenchymal changes due to cirrhosis or depositional diseases. Magnetic resonance (MR) imaging with appropriate sequences (eg, chemical shift techniques) has similarly high sensitivity, and MR spectroscopy provides unique advantages for some applications. However, both are expensive and too complex to be used to monitor steatosis.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2009</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.295085186">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.295085186">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10a-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g10a.jpeg" height="1499" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f10a-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Moderate hepatic steatosis in a 58-year-old man with a history of alcohol abuse. Opposed-phase MR imaging was performed with a 1.5-T system. <b>(a)</b> In-phase (TR/TE = 139/4.76) MR image obtained at the level of the right liver lobe and spleen shows a signal intensity ratio of 309/187 = 1.65. <b>(b)</b> Out-of-phase (TR/TE = 139/2.38) MR image, obtained at the same level as <b>a</b>, shows a signal intensity ratio of 207/198 = 1.05. Calculated by using the Dixon method, the percentage of liver fat is [(1.65 − 1.05)/(2 · 1.65)] · 100 = 18%, a finding indicative mild to moderate steatosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f10a-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f10b-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g10b.jpeg" height="1501" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f10b-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Moderate hepatic steatosis in a 58-year-old man with a history of alcohol abuse. Opposed-phase MR imaging was performed with a 1.5-T system. <b>(a)</b> In-phase (TR/TE = 139/4.76) MR image obtained at the level of the right liver lobe and spleen shows a signal intensity ratio of 309/187 = 1.65. <b>(b)</b> Out-of-phase (TR/TE = 139/2.38) MR image, obtained at the same level as <b>a</b>, shows a signal intensity ratio of 207/198 = 1.05. Calculated by using the Dixon method, the percentage of liver fat is [(1.65 − 1.05)/ (2 · 1.65)] · 100 = 18%, a finding indicative mild to moderate steatosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f10b-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11a-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g11a.jpeg" height="1368" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f11a-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Severe hepatic steatosis in a 27-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted non–fat-saturated fast SE (TR/TE = 6951.3/64.0) MR image obtained at the level of the right liver lobe and spleen shows a hepatic-to-splenic signal intensity ratio of 49/175 = 0.28. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted fat-saturated fast SE (TR/TE = 6951.3/177.0) MR image, obtained at the same level as <b>a</b>, shows a signal intensity ratio of 8/63 = 0.13. From these combined findings, the percentage of liver fat can be calculated as [(0.28 − 0.13)/0.28] · 100 = 54%.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f11a-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f11b-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g11b.jpeg" height="1368" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f11b-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Severe hepatic steatosis in a 27-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Axial T2-weighted non–fat-saturated fast SE (TR/TE = 6951.3/64.0) MR image obtained at the level of the right liver lobe and spleen shows a hepatic-to-splenic signal intensity ratio of 49/175 = 0.28. <b>(b)</b> Axial T2-weighted fat-saturated fast SE (TR/TE = 6951.3/177.0) MR image, obtained at the same level as <b>a</b>, shows a signal intensity ratio of 8/63 = 0.13. From these combined findings, the percentage of liver fat can be calculated as [(0.28 − 0.13)/0.28] · 100 = 54%.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f11b-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f12a-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g12a.jpeg" height="1195" width="1386" aria-labelledby="f12a-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> MR images with overlay demonstrate the technique for single-voxel spectroscopic measurement: The voxel is selected by placing an ROI on localizer MR images in the transverse <b>(a)</b>, sagittal <b>(b)</b>, and coronal <b>(c)</b> planes. The central box containing the cross icon represents the ROI, and the vertical and horizontal dotted lines represent saturation bands.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f12a-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f12b-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g12b.jpeg" height="1380" width="1656" aria-labelledby="f12b-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> MR images with overlay demonstrate the technique for single-voxel spectroscopic measurement: The voxel is selected by placing an ROI on localizer MR images in the transverse <b>(a)</b>, sagittal <b>(b)</b>, and coronal <b>(c)</b> planes. The central box containing the cross icon represents the ROI, and the vertical and horizontal dotted lines represent saturation bands.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f12b-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f12c-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g12c.jpeg" height="1381" width="1602" aria-labelledby="f12c-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span> MR images with overlay demonstrate the technique for single-voxel spectroscopic measurement: The voxel is selected by placing an ROI on localizer MR images in the transverse <b>(a)</b>, sagittal <b>(b)</b>, and coronal <b>(c)</b> planes. The central box containing the cross icon represents the ROI, and the vertical and horizontal dotted lines represent saturation bands.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f12c-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f13-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23l13x.jpeg" height="711" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f13-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13</span> Graph represents a normal liver spectrum obtained with hydrogen 1 (<sup>1</sup>H) MR spectroscopy. Three lipid peaks are produced by CH, CH<sub>2</sub>, and CH<sub>3</sub> resonances at 1.9–2.3 ppm, 1.1–1.5 ppm, and 0.8–1.1 ppm, respectively. The spectral distribution of metabolites includes a glutamine and glutamate complex <i>(GLx)</i> peak at 2.2–2.6 ppm, a choline <i>(Cho)</i> peak at 3.0–3.3 ppm, and a glycogen and glucose complex <i>(Glyu)</i> peak at 3.6–3.9 ppm.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f13-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f14-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23l14x.jpeg" height="959" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f14-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14</span> Graph shows a normal <sup>1</sup>H MR spectrum obtained in healthy liver <i>(a)</i> in comparison with elevated lipid peaks in the presence of mild <i>(b)</i> and severe <i>(c)</i> fatty infiltration.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f14-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f15a-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23l15a.jpeg" height="989" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f15a-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span> Comparison of findings at <sup>1</sup>H MR spectroscopy and liver biopsy in a 45-year-old woman with nonalcoholic fatty liver disease. The elevated choline peak (arrow in <b>a</b>) and decreased ratio of choline to total lipids (0.17) correspond well with the histopathologic finding of stage 2 fibrosis (arrow in <b>b</b>). (Only the choline and lipid peaks are shown in <b>a</b>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f15a-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f15b-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23c15b.jpeg" height="992" width="1101" aria-labelledby="f15b-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span> Comparison of findings at <sup>1</sup>H MR spectroscopy and liver biopsy in a 45-year-old woman with nonalcoholic fatty liver disease. The elevated choline peak (arrow in <b>a</b>) and decreased ratio of choline to total lipids (0.17) correspond well with the histopathologic finding of stage 2 fibrosis (arrow in <b>b</b>). (Only the choline and lipid peaks are shown in <b>a</b>.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f15b-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f16a-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23l16a.jpeg" height="965" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f16a-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> Lipid peaks from <sup>1</sup>H MR spectra obtained in a 43-year-old man before <b>(a)</b> and 3 months after <b>(b)</b> the initiation of pioglitazone therapy for treatment of HIV-associated lipodystrophy show a good response, with a decrease in the hepatic fat concentration from 0.082 to 0.061 mM. (Only the lipid peaks are shown.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f16a-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f16b-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23l16b.jpeg" height="968" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f16b-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> Lipid peaks from <sup>1</sup>H MR spectra obtained in a 43-year-old man before <b>(a)</b> and 3 months after <b>(b)</b> the initiation of pioglitazone therapy for treatment of HIV-associated lipodystrophy show a good response, with a decrease in the hepatic fat concentration from 0.082 to 0.061 mM. (Only the lipid peaks are shown.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f16b-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1a-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23c01a.jpeg" height="865" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f1a-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1a</span> Spectrum of fatty liver disease. Photographs show cut surfaces of livers with simple steatosis <b>(a)</b> and cirrhosis <b>(b)</b>. In <b>a</b>, the mosaic pattern of yellowish discolorations in perivenular areas is produced by the preferential accumulation of fat in those locations. In <b>b</b>, the liver is abnormally small, predominantly tan-white, and nodular in appearance, features that are characteristic of micronodular cirrhosis. The liver capsule in <b>b</b> is nodular, not smooth like that in <b>a.</b> (Fig 1a courtesy of Edward C. Klatt, MD, Mercer University School of Medicine, Macon, Ga.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f1a-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f1b-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23c01b.jpeg" height="691" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f1b-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1b</span> Spectrum of fatty liver disease. Photographs show cut surfaces of livers with simple steatosis <b>(a)</b> and cirrhosis <b>(b)</b>. In <b>a</b>, the mosaic pattern of yellowish discolorations in perivenular areas is produced by the preferential accumulation of fat in those locations. In <b>b</b>, the liver is abnormally small, predominantly tan-white, and nodular in appearance, features that are characteristic of micronodular cirrhosis. The liver capsule in <b>b</b> is nodular, not smooth like that in <b>a.</b> (Fig 1a courtesy of Edward C. Klatt, MD, Mercer University School of Medicine, Macon, Ga.)<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f1b-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f2a-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g02a.jpeg" height="1424" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f2a-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2a</span> Axial CT images show progression of nonalcoholic fatty liver disease from steatosis to fibrosis. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan shows diffuse fatty infiltration of liver with hepatic attenuation (26 HU) well below splenic attenuation (44 HU). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan obtained 10 years later demonstrates hepatic surface nodularity (arrows), a finding suggestive of cirrhosis. The diagnosis, based on liver biopsy, was micronodular cirrhosis with prominent sinusoidal fibrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f2a-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f2b-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g02b.jpeg" height="1424" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f2b-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2b</span> Axial CT images show progression of nonalcoholic fatty liver disease from steatosis to fibrosis. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan shows diffuse fatty infiltration of liver with hepatic attenuation (26 HU) well below splenic attenuation (44 HU). <b>(b)</b> Axial contrast-enhanced CT scan obtained 10 years later demonstrates hepatic surface nodularity (arrows), a finding suggestive of cirrhosis. The diagnosis, based on liver biopsy, was micronodular cirrhosis with prominent sinusoidal fibrosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f2b-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3a-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23c03a.jpeg" height="1005" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f3a-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3a</span> High-power photomicrographs (<b>a</b> and <b>c</b>, hematoxylin-eosin stain; <b>b</b>, trichrome stain) show the histologic features of each stage of fatty liver disease. <b>(a)</b> In the initial stage (simple steatosis), numerous large lipid vacuoles (asterisks) displace the nuclei of hepatocytes to the periphery of cytoplasm. <b>(b)</b> In the intermediate stage (steatohepatitis), hepatocytes with ballooning degeneration (arrows) are seen with pericellular “chicken-wire” fibrosis (blue-stained areas). <b>(c)</b> In the advanced stage (steatohepatitis with cirrhosis), a thick fibrous band (arrows) surrounds the nodular parenchyma with fat-laden hepatocytes (oval).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f3a-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3b-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23c03b.jpeg" height="1006" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f3b-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3b</span> High-power photomicrographs (<b>a</b> and <b>c</b>, hematoxylin-eosin stain; <b>b</b>, trichrome stain) show the histologic features of each stage of fatty liver disease. <b>(a)</b> In the initial stage (simple steatosis), numerous large lipid vacuoles (asterisks) displace the nuclei of hepatocytes to the periphery of cytoplasm. <b>(b)</b> In the intermediate stage (steatohepatitis), hepatocytes with ballooning degeneration (arrows) are seen with pericellular “chicken-wire” fibrosis (blue-stained areas). <b>(c)</b> In the advanced stage (steatohepatitis with cirrhosis), a thick fibrous band (arrows) surrounds the nodular parenchyma with fat-laden hepatocytes (oval).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f3b-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f3c-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23c03c.jpeg" height="1002" width="1280" aria-labelledby="f3c-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3c</span> High-power photomicrographs (<b>a</b> and <b>c</b>, hematoxylin-eosin stain; <b>b</b>, trichrome stain) show the histologic features of each stage of fatty liver disease. <b>(a)</b> In the initial stage (simple steatosis), numerous large lipid vacuoles (asterisks) displace the nuclei of hepatocytes to the periphery of cytoplasm. <b>(b)</b> In the intermediate stage (steatohepatitis), hepatocytes with ballooning degeneration (arrows) are seen with pericellular “chicken-wire” fibrosis (blue-stained areas). <b>(c)</b> In the advanced stage (steatohepatitis with cirrhosis), a thick fibrous band (arrows) surrounds the nodular parenchyma with fat-laden hepatocytes (oval).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f3c-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f4a-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g04a.jpeg" height="1411" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f4a-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Reduction of hepatic steatosis in a 67-year-old woman after gastric bypass surgery for morbid obesity. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal US image obtained before surgery demonstrates severe fatty infiltration of the liver <i>(L)</i>, with obscuration of the vascular outlines and diaphragmatic margin. <i>K</i> = kidney. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal US image obtained 6 months after surgery shows minimal to mild fatty infiltration, a finding indicative of a significant reduction of hepatic steatosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f4a-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f4b-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g04b.jpeg" height="1411" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f4b-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Reduction of hepatic steatosis in a 67-year-old woman after gastric bypass surgery for morbid obesity. <b>(a)</b> Sagittal US image obtained before surgery demonstrates severe fatty infiltration of the liver <i>(L)</i>, with obscuration of the vascular outlines and diaphragmatic margin. <i>K</i> = kidney. <b>(b)</b> Sagittal US image obtained 6 months after surgery shows minimal to mild fatty infiltration, a finding indicative of a significant reduction of hepatic steatosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f4b-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5a-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g05a.jpeg" height="1349" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f5a-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Chemotherapy-associated steatohepatitis in a 70-year-old woman undergoing treatment for metastatic transitional cell carcinoma of the left ureter. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan obtained before chemotherapy shows hepatic parenchymal attenuation (66 HU) greater than splenic attenuation (55 HU), with no evidence of hepatic steatosis. <b>(b–e)</b> Images obtained 18 months later, during chemotherapy, demonstrate the development of hepatic steatosis. Transverse US image of the right hepatic lobe <b>(b)</b> depicts an increase in liver echogenicity with obscuration of the portal venule walls, findings indicative of moderate to severe fatty infiltration. Axial unenhanced CT scan <b>(c)</b> shows hepatic attenuation (44 HU) significantly lower than splenic attenuation (53 HU), with mild heterogeneity. Axial in-phase <b>(d)</b> and out-of-phase <b>(e)</b> MR images obtained at the same level show moderate liver steatosis. Calculated according to the Dixon method, the fat percentage in the liver is 23%.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f5a-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5b-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g05b.jpeg" height="1349" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f5b-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Chemotherapy-associated steatohepatitis in a 70-year-old woman undergoing treatment for metastatic transitional cell carcinoma of the left ureter. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan obtained before chemotherapy shows hepatic parenchymal attenuation (66 HU) greater than splenic attenuation (55 HU), with no evidence of hepatic steatosis. <b>(b–e)</b> Images obtained 18 months later, during chemotherapy, demonstrate the development of hepatic steatosis. Transverse US image of the right hepatic lobe <b>(b)</b> depicts an increase in liver echogenicity with obscuration of the portal venule walls, findings indicative of moderate to severe fatty infiltration. Axial unenhanced CT scan <b>(c)</b> shows hepatic attenuation (44 HU) significantly lower than splenic attenuation (53 HU), with mild heterogeneity. Axial in-phase <b>(d)</b> and out-of-phase <b>(e)</b> MR images obtained at the same level show moderate liver steatosis. Calculated according to the Dixon method, the fat percentage in the liver is 23%.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f5b-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5c-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g05c.jpeg" height="1351" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f5c-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5c</span> Chemotherapy-associated steatohepatitis in a 70-year-old woman undergoing treatment for metastatic transitional cell carcinoma of the left ureter. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan obtained before chemotherapy shows hepatic parenchymal attenuation (66 HU) greater than splenic attenuation (55 HU), with no evidence of hepatic steatosis. <b>(b–e)</b> Images obtained 18 months later, during chemotherapy, demonstrate the development of hepatic steatosis. Transverse US image of the right hepatic lobe <b>(b)</b> depicts an increase in liver echogenicity with obscuration of the portal venule walls, findings indicative of moderate to severe fatty infiltration. Axial unenhanced CT scan <b>(c)</b> shows hepatic attenuation (44 HU) significantly lower than splenic attenuation (53 HU), with mild heterogeneity. Axial in-phase <b>(d)</b> and out-of-phase <b>(e)</b> MR images obtained at the same level show moderate liver steatosis. Calculated according to the Dixon method, the fat percentage in the liver is 23%.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f5c-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5d-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g05d.jpeg" height="1351" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f5d-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5d</span> Chemotherapy-associated steatohepatitis in a 70-year-old woman undergoing treatment for metastatic transitional cell carcinoma of the left ureter. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan obtained before chemotherapy shows hepatic parenchymal attenuation (66 HU) greater than splenic attenuation (55 HU), with no evidence of hepatic steatosis. <b>(b–e)</b> Images obtained 18 months later, during chemotherapy, demonstrate the development of hepatic steatosis. Transverse US image of the right hepatic lobe <b>(b)</b> depicts an increase in liver echogenicity with obscuration of the portal venule walls, findings indicative of moderate to severe fatty infiltration. Axial unenhanced CT scan <b>(c)</b> shows hepatic attenuation (44 HU) significantly lower than splenic attenuation (53 HU), with mild heterogeneity. Axial in-phase <b>(d)</b> and out-of-phase <b>(e)</b> MR images obtained at the same level show moderate liver steatosis. Calculated according to the Dixon method, the fat percentage in the liver is 23%.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f5d-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f5e-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g05e.jpeg" height="1349" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f5e-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5e</span> Chemotherapy-associated steatohepatitis in a 70-year-old woman undergoing treatment for metastatic transitional cell carcinoma of the left ureter. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan obtained before chemotherapy shows hepatic parenchymal attenuation (66 HU) greater than splenic attenuation (55 HU), with no evidence of hepatic steatosis. <b>(b–e)</b> Images obtained 18 months later, during chemotherapy, demonstrate the development of hepatic steatosis. Transverse US image of the right hepatic lobe <b>(b)</b> depicts an increase in liver echogenicity with obscuration of the portal venule walls, findings indicative of moderate to severe fatty infiltration. Axial unenhanced CT scan <b>(c)</b> shows hepatic attenuation (44 HU) significantly lower than splenic attenuation (53 HU), with mild heterogeneity. Axial in-phase <b>(d)</b> and out-of-phase <b>(e)</b> MR images obtained at the same level show moderate liver steatosis. Calculated according to the Dixon method, the fat percentage in the liver is 23%.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f5e-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6a-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g06a.jpeg" height="1481" width="1548" aria-labelledby="f6a-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Longitudinal US images show mild to severe fatty liver disease in three different patients. <b>(a)</b> Mild fatty infiltration in the right hepatic lobe is depicted as a minimal increase in echogenicity of the liver in comparison with that of the renal cortex <i>(K).</i> The diaphragm (arrow) and intrahepatic vessels (arrowhead) appear normal. <b>(b)</b> Moderate fatty infiltration is demonstrated by a moderate increase in echogenicity of the liver and slightly impaired depiction of the diaphragm (arrow) and intrahepatic vessels (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Severe fatty infiltration is shown as a marked increase in liver echogenicity with poor penetration of the deep parenchyma (<b>*</b>) and impaired visualization of the intrahepatic vessels (arrowhead) and diaphragm (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f6a-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6b-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g06b.jpeg" height="1630" width="1710" aria-labelledby="f6b-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Longitudinal US images show mild to severe fatty liver disease in three different patients. <b>(a)</b> Mild fatty infiltration in the right hepatic lobe is depicted as a minimal increase in echogenicity of the liver in comparison with that of the renal cortex <i>(K).</i> The diaphragm (arrow) and intrahepatic vessels (arrowhead) appear normal. <b>(b)</b> Moderate fatty infiltration is demonstrated by a moderate increase in echogenicity of the liver and slightly impaired depiction of the diaphragm (arrow) and intrahepatic vessels (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Severe fatty infiltration is shown as a marked increase in liver echogenicity with poor penetration of the deep parenchyma (<b>*</b>) and impaired visualization of the intrahepatic vessels (arrowhead) and diaphragm (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f6b-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f6c-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g06c.jpeg" height="1749" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f6c-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span> Longitudinal US images show mild to severe fatty liver disease in three different patients. <b>(a)</b> Mild fatty infiltration in the right hepatic lobe is depicted as a minimal increase in echogenicity of the liver in comparison with that of the renal cortex <i>(K).</i> The diaphragm (arrow) and intrahepatic vessels (arrowhead) appear normal. <b>(b)</b> Moderate fatty infiltration is demonstrated by a moderate increase in echogenicity of the liver and slightly impaired depiction of the diaphragm (arrow) and intrahepatic vessels (arrowhead). <b>(c)</b> Severe fatty infiltration is shown as a marked increase in liver echogenicity with poor penetration of the deep parenchyma (<b>*</b>) and impaired visualization of the intrahepatic vessels (arrowhead) and diaphragm (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f6c-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7a-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g07a.jpeg" height="1499" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f7a-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Calculation of the hepatic attenuation index for fat quantification at CT. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan demonstrates normal hepatic and splenic attenuation, with a hepatic attenuation index of 1.1. The index is calculated by dividing the average hepatic attenuation measured in Hounsfield units by the average splenic attenuation measured in Hounsfield units. <b>(b)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan obtained in a 45-year-old man with severe hepatic steatosis shows an obvious decrease in average hepatic attenuation in comparison with average splenic attenuation (hepatic attenuation index, 0.22). The decreased hepatic attenuation allows clear visualization of portal vein branches.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f7a-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f7b-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g07b.jpeg" height="1501" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f7b-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Calculation of the hepatic attenuation index for fat quantification at CT. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan demonstrates normal hepatic and splenic attenuation, with a hepatic attenuation index of 1.1. The index is calculated by dividing the average hepatic attenuation measured in Hounsfield units by the average splenic attenuation measured in Hounsfield units. <b>(b)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan obtained in a 45-year-old man with severe hepatic steatosis shows an obvious decrease in average hepatic attenuation in comparison with average splenic attenuation (hepatic attenuation index, 0.22). The decreased hepatic attenuation allows clear visualization of portal vein branches.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f7b-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f8a-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g08a.jpeg" height="1391" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f8a-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> Dual-energy CT evaluation of liver in a 45-year-old male potential donor for living transplantation. Axial unenhanced CT scans obtained at 140 kVp <b>(a)</b> and 80 kVp <b>(b)</b> show a hepatic attenuation difference of 9 HU, a finding indicative of moderate hepatic steatosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f8a-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f8b-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g08b.jpeg" height="1391" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f8b-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> Dual-energy CT evaluation of liver in a 45-year-old male potential donor for living transplantation. Axial unenhanced CT scans obtained at 140 kVp <b>(a)</b> and 80 kVp <b>(b)</b> show a hepatic attenuation difference of 9 HU, a finding indicative of moderate hepatic steatosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f8b-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f9a-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g09a.jpeg" height="1499" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f9a-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Mild hepatic steatosis in a 46-year-old woman with abdominal pain and elevated levels of hepatic transaminases. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan shows no significant fatty change in the liver, with hepatic attenuation of 67 HU and splenic attenuation of 50 HU. MR imaging was performed a week later. <b>(b)</b> In-phase (TR msec/TE msec = 180/4.42) MR image shows a hepatic-to-splenic signal intensity ratio of 436/331 = 1.31. <b>(c)</b> Out-of-phase (TR/TE = 180/2.17) MR image shows a lower hepatic-to-splenic signal intensity ratio of 368/333 = 1.10. Calculated by using the Dixon method, the percentage of liver fat is [(1.31 − 1.10)/(2 · 1.31)] · 100 = 8%, a finding indicative of steatosis. A subsequent liver biopsy helped confirm the presence of mild hepatic steatosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f9a-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f9b-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g09b.jpeg" height="1499" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f9b-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Mild hepatic steatosis in a 46-year-old woman with abdominal pain and elevated levels of hepatic transaminases. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan shows no significant fatty change in the liver, with hepatic attenuation of 67 HU and splenic attenuation of 50 HU. MR imaging was performed a week later. <b>(b)</b> In-phase (TR msec/TE msec = 180/4.42) MR image shows a hepatic-to-splenic signal intensity ratio of 436/331 = 1.31. <b>(c)</b> Out-of-phase (TR/TE = 180/2.17) MR image shows a lower hepatic-to-splenic signal intensity ratio of 368/333 = 1.10. Calculated by using the Dixon method, the percentage of liver fat is [(1.31 − 1.10)/(2 · 1.31)] · 100 = 8%, a finding indicative of steatosis. A subsequent liver biopsy helped confirm the presence of mild hepatic steatosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f9b-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="f9c-0291253" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.295085186/asset/images/g09se23g09c.jpeg" height="1499" width="1800" aria-labelledby="f9c-0291253" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9c</span> Mild hepatic steatosis in a 46-year-old woman with abdominal pain and elevated levels of hepatic transaminases. <b>(a)</b> Axial unenhanced CT scan shows no significant fatty change in the liver, with hepatic attenuation of 67 HU and splenic attenuation of 50 HU. MR imaging was performed a week later. <b>(b)</b> In-phase (TR msec/TE msec = 180/4.42) MR image shows a hepatic-to-splenic signal intensity ratio of 436/331 = 1.31. <b>(c)</b> Out-of-phase (TR/TE = 180/2.17) MR image shows a lower hepatic-to-splenic signal intensity ratio of 368/333 = 1.10. Calculated by using the Dixon method, the percentage of liver fat is [(1.31 − 1.10)/(2 · 1.31)] · 100 = 8%, a finding indicative of steatosis. A subsequent liver biopsy helped confirm the presence of mild hepatic steatosis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.295085186&amp;id=f9c-0291253">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="b1-0291253" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Adams LA, Lymp JF, St Sauver J, et al. The natural history of nonalcoholic fatty liver disease: a population-based cohort study. <em>Gastroenterology</em> 2005; 129:113–121.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1053/j.gastro.2005.04.014">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16012941/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=The+natural+history+of+nonalcoholic+fatty+liver+disease%3A+a+population-based+cohort+study&amp;author=LA+Adams&amp;author=JF+Lymp&amp;author=J+St+Sauver&amp;publication_year=2005&amp;journal=Gastroenterology&amp;pages=113-121&amp;doi=10.1053%2Fj.gastro.2005.04.014&amp;pmid=16012941">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="b2-0291253" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Browning JD, Szczepaniak LS, Dobbins R, et al. Prevalence of hepatic steatosis in an urban population in the United States: impact of ethnicity. <em>Hepatology</em> 2004;40:1387–1395.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1002/hep.20466">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/15565570/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Prevalence+of+hepatic+steatosis+in+an+urban+population+in+the+United+States%3A+impact+of+ethnicity&amp;author=JD+Browning&amp;author=LS+Szczepaniak&amp;author=R+Dobbins&amp;publication_year=2004&amp;journal=Hepatology&amp;pages=1387-1395&amp;doi=10.1002%2Fhep.20466&amp;pmid=15565570">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">3.</div><div id="b3-0291253" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Adams LA, Angulo P, Abraham SC, Torgerson H, Brandhagen D. The effect of the metabolic syndrome, hepatic steatosis and steatohepatitis on liver fibrosis in hereditary hemochromatosis. <em>Liver Int</em> 2006;26:298–304.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1111/j.1478-3231.2005.01238.x">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-